</aside>

<p>As far as the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> part, it seems like your goal  (or at least your code) is trying to do <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> Auto-tuning, which will not be effectively performed by this code. Effectively, the moment the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> crosses the threshhold, this considers it “tuned”. This is unlikely to accurately reflect the performance you want out of a <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span>. A tuned <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> is more than about getting your error to zero, but about maintaining system stability (not oscillating), minimizing overshooting, and maintaining a low error when your system is disturbed.</p>
<p>A perfectly tuned system will respond with a damped response: Immediately recovering from a disturbance in the lowest possible amount of time, without any overshoot beyond the setpoint, and without oscillating/settling. Doing this either requires either a lot of math for system dynamics, a lot of time, or a very, very well developed auto-calibration process.</p>
<p>If you’re using SysID (it’s worth it, trust me) then this actually helps provide these values based on your system’s response to changing motor outputs.  <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/advanced-controls/system-identification/analyzing-gains.html" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Analyzing Data — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation</a></p>
<p>If you want to roll your own tuner, there’s a number of math-heavy white papers, but this might help walk you through the concepts at a more casual level.  <a href="http://brettbeauregard.com/blog/2012/01/arduino-pid-autotune-library/" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Arduino PID Autotune Library « Project Blog</a></p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-04-09T06:22:36.035Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":182,"readers_count":181,"score":71.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":461838,"topic_slug":"pidlib","display_username":"Dan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"http://brettbeauregard.com/blog/2012/01/arduino-pid-autotune-library/","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Arduino PID Autotune Library « Project Blog","clicks":10},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/advanced-controls/system-identification/analyzing-gains.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Analyzing Data — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":7},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/telemetry/writing-sendable-classes.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Writing Your Own Sendable Classes — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":6}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44763,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"2811 Programming Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/pidlib/461838/8","custom_user_title":"2811 Programming Mentor","reactions":[{"id":"