<p>Great post overall, but in my experience manual tuning can be <em>very fast</em> provided you have a solid understanding of the system you’re trying to tune and are approaching it with a sound control strategy.</p>
<p>A simple exponential search works remarkably well in practice.</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-04-09T12:39:20.231Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":129,"readers_count":128,"score":30.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":461838,"topic_slug":"pidlib","display_username":"Eli Barnett","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":12381,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!"},"post_url":"/t/pidlib/461838/9","custom_user_title":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3356211,"name":"","username":"Mateo","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/f4b2a3/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-04-09T13:30:04.595Z","cooked":"<p>so you think itd work? cause thats what ive found in my pid tuning, just start with a really small P value and move it up slowly. and the point of this is not to be instant, its to be something that you can leave running, and let it slowly hone in.</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-04-09T13:30:04.595Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":9,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":115,"readers_count":114,"score":23.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":461838,"topic_slug":"pidlib","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":12381,"username":"Oblarg","name":"Eli Barnett","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/oblarg/{size}/161674_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":58360,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/pidlib/461838/10","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3356228,"name":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/slab-mr.thomas/{size}/182153_2.png","created_at":"2024-04-09T13:45:07.255Z","cooked":"<p>I didn’t want to discourage you since I, too, make hacky <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tuning stuff occasionally (but with limited scope and I have my reasons). Working through all this can be a great learning experience.</p>
<p><a class="mention" href="/u/oblarg">@Oblarg</a> is right about the usual ease of tuning and I’ll water his response down some by saying the students don’t have to have solid understanding to be successful tuning <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> in a few minutes. A brief lecture by me drawing some typical response curves to start them off normally suffices. They know what to expect with their exponential search for values (0.000001, 0.00001, 0.0001, 0.001. , etc) and are ready to hit disable.</p>
<p>The relay method referenced by <a class="mention" href="/u/tekdemo">@tekdemo</a> is effective, clever tuning and works. However, the code referenced, unless recently updated, is buggy. I converted the Arduino version to roboRIO (or was it cRIO?) C++ and then Java. It tunes a system in about 1/4 second. There is a lot of variation so run it 3 or 4 times, eyeball the average, and you have pretty good tuning ready to fine-tune-manually for even better results. <a href="https://github.com/tom131313/PID-AutoTune-Library" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">GitHub - tom131313/PID-AutoTune-Library: Java version of the Arduino-PID-AutoTune-Library</a></p>
<p>To answer your question on reverse direction (phase) - to make the output less if the input is more then use a negative sign on the output. This is effectively the <code>setInverse(true)</code> we use on motor controllers.</p>
<p>Why did I bother even looking at the relay tuning scheme and code? Long ago there was not the documentation by the motor controller manufacturers and WPILib on <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> control. We were on our own. Now there is adequate description of how-to and even packaged code like the SYSID, Phoenix Tuner X, and Rev client all of which make tuning much easy than the good ole days.</p>","post_number":11,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-04-09T13:45:07.255Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":114,"readers_count":113,"score":42.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":461838,"topic_slug":"pidlib","display_username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/tom131313/PID-AutoTune-Library","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"GitHub - tom131313/PID-AutoTune-Library: Java version of the Arduino-PID-AutoTune-Library","clicks":4}],"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":58360,"username":"Mateo","name":"","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/f4b2a3/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":24594,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/pidlib/461838/11","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3356245,"name":"","username":"Mateo","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/f4b2a3/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-04-09T14:01:46.520Z","cooked":"<p>1/4 of a second is rlly quick! so do you think i should try to make it more like the code <a class="mention" href="/u/tekdemo">@tekdemo</a> referenced?</p>","post_number":12,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-04-09T14:27:56.268Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":11,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":101,"readers_count":100,"score":25.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":461838,"topic_slug":"pidlib","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":24594,"username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","name":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/slab-mr.thomas/{size}/182153_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":58360,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/pidlib/461838/12","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3356288,"name":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/slab-mr.thomas/{size}/182153_2.png","created_at":"2024-04-09T14:35:44.627Z","cooked":"<details>
<summary>
More like a personal note on my priorities and I don't know OP's priorities</summary>
<p>I forked the original Arduino library code and debugged it and added a feature or two that I saw others had made in their own forks. Later I made the Java version - essentially identical code; old C++ was the same as old Java.</p>
<p>I don’t use the AutoTuner mostly because the setup of the system is tedious compared to using, for example, the Phoenix tuner. With the Phoenix tuner the students can tune their system faster than writing code to wrap around or insert into their robot code.</p>
<p>Playing with <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tuning can be fun and instructive and start you along learning control theory but if you have limited time is it important compared to other projects you could be doing? Given the good <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tools currently available my team sees learning effective application of PathPlanner and Choreo and maybe chasing game pieces with OpenCV or AI a good use of our time to be more competitive. There is a recent thread about off-season projects and they all sound better to me than fussing with writing <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tools. Learn how to use the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tuning tools and use them again for troubleshooting system problems during competitions and you will be well-served.</p>
<p>The caveat to my statement of my team priorities is we don’t have time to invent much from scratch. We use <span class="abbreviation">COTS<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Commercial, off-the-shelf"></template></span> resources (almost) as much as possible. For example, it broke my heart a little to buy LImeLight Vision cameras instead of doing our own vision as we had done for years. Our code was better but took too much time that the students were not willing to do at the expense of doing other things. All this can be somewhat cyclic as classes of students pass through and a freshman team ages to more capable seniors and highly depends on if we get one extremely motivated student to do special projects and then what special project do they pick?</p>
